message.content:
We start by gathering the ending (latest) numbers from each of the three statements.

──────────────────────────────
Step 1. Extract the key amounts (all “End_amount” values):

• From the Balance Sheet:
 – Cash on Hand = 2,105,753.37  
 – Bank Deposits = 559,055.66  
 – Interest Receivable = 6,494.02  
 – Accounts Receivable = 335,639.38  
 – Inventory = 7,446,940.00  
 – Total Current Assets = 10,453,882.43  
 – Fixed Assets = 11,415,664.34  
 – Accumulated Depreciation = 132,103.78  
 – Total Non-current Assets = 11,283,560.56  
 – Total Assets = 21,737,442.99  
 – Accounts Payable = 5,596,070.00  
 – Taxes Payable = 41,840.70  
 – Total Current Liabilities = 5,637,910.70  
 – Paid-in Capital = 16,000,000.00  
 – Retained Earnings = 99,532.29  
 – Total Owner’s Equity = 16,099,532.29

The total liabilities can be deduced as:  
 Total Liabilities = Total Assets – Owner’s Equity  
  = 21,737,442.99 – 16,099,532.29  
  = 5,637,910.70  
(which matches the given Total Current Liabilities, assuming no non–current debt)

──────────────────────────────
Step 2. Extract numbers from the Cash Flow Statement:
 – Net Cash Flow from Operating Activities = –1,919,526.63  
 (The other operating items add up to this value.)  
 – Depreciation (for reference in some ratios) = 132,103.78

──────────────────────────────
Step 3. Extract numbers from the Income Statement:
 – Total Revenue = 836,813.79  
 – Cost of Goods Sold = 544,970.00  
 – Net Profit = 99,532.29

──────────────────────────────
Now compute each ratio:

1. Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
 Definition: (Operating Cash Flow) ÷ (Current Liabilities)  
 Calculation: –1,919,526.63 ÷ 5,637,910.70 ≈ –0.34

2. Debt to Equity Ratio  
 Definition: (Total Liabilities) ÷ (Owner’s Equity)  
 Calculation: 5,637,910.70 ÷ 16,099,532.29 ≈ 0.35

3. Total Asset Turnover Ratio  
 Definition: (Total Revenue) ÷ (Total Assets)  
 Calculation: 836,813.79 ÷ 21,737,442.99 ≈ 0.0385  
 Rounded to two decimals: 0.04

4. Quick Ratio  
 Definition: (Cash + Bank Deposits + Accounts Receivable + Interest Receivable) ÷ (Current Liabilities)  
 First compute the numerator:  
  Cash on Hand + Bank Deposits = 2,105,753.37 + 559,055.66 = 2,664,809.03  
  Add Accounts Receivable: 2,664,809.03 + 335,639.38 = 2,1? 2,664,809.03 + 335,639.38 = 3,000,448.41  
  Add Interest Receivable: 3,000,448.41 + 6,494.02 = 3,006,942.43  
 Then, Quick Ratio = 3,006,942.43 ÷ 5,637,910.70 ≈ 0.533, i.e. about 0.53

5. Operating Cash Flow Ratio  
 Definition: Often the same as the Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio  
 Calculation: –1,919,526.63 ÷ 5,637,910.70 ≈ –0.34

6. Return on Equity (ROE)  
 Definition: (Net Profit) ÷ (Owner’s Equity)  
 Calculation: 99,532.29 ÷ 16,099,532.29 ≈ 0.00618  
 Expressed as a percentage: 0.62%

7. Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio  
 Definition: (Total Revenue) ÷ (Accounts Receivable)  
 Calculation: 836,813.79 ÷ 335,639.38 ≈ 2.49

──────────────────────────────
Thus, the calculated ratios are:

• Operating Cash Flow to Current Liabilities Ratio: –0.34  
• Debt to Equity Ratio: 0.35  
• Total Asset Turnover Ratio: 0.04  
• Quick Ratio: 0.53  
• Operating Cash Flow Ratio: –0.34  
• Return on Equity (ROE): 0.62%  
• Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio: 2.49

──────────────────────────────

    "Operating Cash Flow Ratio": "-0.34",
    "Return on Equity (ROE)": "0.62%",
    "Accounts Receivable Turnover Ratio": "2.49"
  }
}
